{"id":2191,"date":"2018-09-24T11:43:41","date_gmt":"2018-09-24T18:43:41","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/davidegerosa.com\/?p=2191"},"modified":"2018-09-24T11:43:41","modified_gmt":"2018-09-24T18:43:41","slug":"high-accuracy-mass-spin-and-recoil-predictions-of-generic-black-hole-merger-remnants","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/davidegerosa.com\/2018\/09\/24\/high-accuracy-mass-spin-and-recoil-predictions-of-generic-black-hole-merger-remnants\/","title":{"rendered":"High-accuracy mass, spin, and recoil predictions of generic black-hole merger remnants"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>Black hole mergers are like a scattering problem. Two black holes come in, and one black hole comes out. The difference is a bunch of gravitational waves. Those are nice, of course, but the remnant black hole is important too! Here we provide accurate predictions of the mass, spin and kick of this remnant given the properties of the two merging black holes. If you need those numbers (want to build a waveform family? or test GR perhaps?) just use our python module <a href=\"https:\/\/github.com\/vijayvarma392\/surfinBH\">surfinBH<\/a>!<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2356\" height=\"994\" src=\"https:\/\/davidegerosa.files.wordpress.com\/2018\/10\/ducks.png\" alt=\"ducks\" class=\"wp-image-2192\" srcset=\"https:\/\/davidegerosa.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/ducks.png 2356w, https:\/\/davidegerosa.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/ducks-300x127.png 300w, https:\/\/davidegerosa.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/ducks-1024x432.png 1024w, https:\/\/davidegerosa.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/ducks-768x324.png 768w, https:\/\/davidegerosa.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/ducks-1536x648.png 1536w, https:\/\/davidegerosa.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/ducks-2048x864.png 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2356px) 100vw, 2356px\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p><em>Bonus note<\/em>. What if you collide ducks instead of black holes?&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Vijay Varma,\u00a0<strong>Davide Gerosa<\/strong>, Fran\u00e7ois H\u00e9bert, Leo C. Stein, Hao Zhang.<br><strong>Physical Review Letters\u00a0<\/strong>122 (2019)\u00a0<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https:\/\/journals.aps.org\/prl\/abstract\/10.1103\/PhysRevLett.122.011101\" target=\"_blank\">011101<\/a>.<br>arXiv:<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"http:\/\/arxiv.org\/abs\/arXiv:1809.09125\" target=\"_blank\">1809.09125<\/a>\u00a0[gr-qc]<br>Press release:\u00a0<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" class=\"externlink\" title=\"Go to http:\/\/www.cam.ac.uk\/research\/news\/new-insights-found-in-black-hole-collisions\/\" href=\"http:\/\/www.caltech.edu\/news\/when-black-holes-collide-85110\" target=\"_blank\">Caltech<\/a>,\u00a0<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https:\/\/news.olemiss.edu\/making-better-predictions-black-hole-smash-ups\/\" target=\"_blank\">Ole Miss<\/a>.<br>Other press coverage:\u00a0<a class=\"externlink\" title=\"Go to http:\/\/www.sciencedaily.com\/releases\/2015\/02\/150226110448.htm\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"http:\/\/www.spacedaily.com\/reports\/Physicists_Create_the_Most_Accurate_Model_Yet_of_Black_Hole_Mergers_999.html\" target=\"_blank\">Space Daily<\/a>,\u00a0<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" class=\"externlink\" title=\"Go to http:\/\/phys.org\/news\/2015-02-insight-black-hole-collisions.html\" href=\"https:\/\/phys.org\/news\/2019-01-physicists-supercomputers-ai-accurate-black.html\" target=\"_blank\">phys.org<\/a>,\u00a0<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https:\/\/www.longroom.com\/discussion\/1340817\/physicists-use-supercomputers-and-ai-to-create-the-most-accurate-model-yet-of-black-hole-mergers\" target=\"_blank\">longroom<\/a>,\u00a0<a rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https:\/\/www.tasnimnews.com\/en\/news\/2019\/01\/25\/1930821\/supercomputers-ai-used-to-create-most-accurate-model-of-black-hole-mergers\" target=\"_blank\">tasnim<\/a>,\u00a0<a r